Good morning everyone,

Today I’m going to explain some important Kubernetes concepts that are heavily used in real-world DevOps and production environments.

These concepts include:
• ConfigMaps
• Secrets
• Network Policies
• cgroups
• RBAC
• Persistent Volumes
and other important Kubernetes components.

Let’s start with ConfigMaps.

ConfigMaps are used to store non-sensitive configuration data separately from the application code.

For example:
• Application URLs
• Environment variables
• Port numbers
• Feature flags

This helps developers update configurations without rebuilding Docker images.

Next are Secrets.

Secrets are used to securely store sensitive information such as:
• Passwords
• API keys
• Access tokens
• Certificates

Unlike ConfigMaps, Secrets are base64 encoded and help separate sensitive data from application code.

In production environments, Secrets are commonly integrated with external tools such as AWS KMS or HashiCorp Vault for stronger security.

Now let’s discuss Network Policies.

Network Policies act like firewalls inside Kubernetes clusters.

By default, all pods can communicate with each other, which may create security risks.

Network Policies allow organizations to control traffic flow between pods and restrict unauthorized communication.

For example:
Frontend applications may be allowed to communicate with backend services, but direct access to database pods can be blocked.

Another important concept is cgroups.

cgroups, or Control Groups, are Linux kernel features used for resource management.

Kubernetes uses cgroups to control:
• CPU usage
• Memory limits
• Resource isolation

This prevents one container from consuming excessive resources and affecting other applications.

Namespaces are also important in Kubernetes.

Namespaces help logically separate environments such as:
• Development
• Testing
• Production

This improves organization and access management inside large clusters.

Next is RBAC, which stands for Role-Based Access Control.

RBAC controls who can access and modify Kubernetes resources.

For example:
Developers may receive read-only access, while administrators receive full cluster permissions.

Persistent Volumes are another critical concept.

Because Kubernetes pods are temporary, Persistent Volumes provide durable storage for applications such as:
• MySQL
• MongoDB
• Kafka

This ensures data remains safe even if pods restart.

Ingress is used for managing external HTTP and HTTPS traffic into Kubernetes clusters.

It provides:
• Domain-based routing
• SSL termination
• Centralized traffic management

In real-world production environments, all these Kubernetes concepts work together to build scalable, secure, and reliable cloud-native applications.

To conclude,

Understanding ConfigMaps, Secrets, Network Policies, cgroups, RBAC, and storage management is extremely important for every DevOps engineer working with Kubernetes in production environments.

Thank you.
